law.text:
In accordance with requirements of the federal Older Americans Act, an ombudsman shall have access to:
long-term care facilities and residents;
the medical and social records of a resident, if:
the ombudsman has the permission of the resident or the legal representative of the resident; or
the resident is unable to consent and has no legal representative;
the records that are necessary to investigate a complaint if:
a legal guardian of the resident refuses to give permission to access the records;
the ombudsman has reasonable cause to believe that the guardian is not acting in the best interests of the resident; and
the ombudsman obtains the approval of the State Long-Term Care Ombudsman;
the administrative records, policies, and documents of long-term care facilities to which the residents or members of the general public have access; and
copies of all licensing and certification records maintained by the Department of Health and Mental Hygiene or any other State unit with respect to long-term care facilities.
